sec.p:
The specimens depicted in the literature and the additional distribution information give rise to the current view that
ssp. draesekei Bang-Haas, 1927
(TL: Songpan, N. Sichuan ), a previously supposed subspecies of
A. procris
from N. Sichuan , is not supported by reliable diagnostic characteristics and already synonymized with the nominate subspecies (
). Accordingly, all populations from Sichuan are currently considered nominotypical, with the exception of the phenotypically divergent population from the upper Dadu River ( Fig. 5 ). Although the topology of this new subspecies, inferred from the Cytb gene, is not monophyletic, this phenomenon is not uncommon because infraspecific differences in pierids do not always manifest in mitochondrial genes (S.J. Hu et al. 2021;
;
) ( Fig. 6 ).

The discovery of the new subspecies in 
Sichuan
is intriguing and unexpected, owing to the absence of notable geographical isolation from other adjacent regions. The morphological divergence of 

A. procris

in Jinchuan and Barkam might be attributed to two factors. The first is that the new subspecies is observed only at relatively low altitudes, as mentioned in the ecological section, where its habitats are constrained by the high mountains. Second, the areas in the upper Dadu River, from Danba, across Jinchuan to W. Barkam, are part of a unique geographical region known as the ‘dry-hot valley’, characterized by high temperatures and low humidity (Y. Hu 
et al.
2021; 

) (
Fig. 5
). Consequently, this new subspecies, driven by such ecological opportunity, may have emerged in the dry-hot valley of the upper Dadu River, probably a case of the early stage of budding speciation (

). Subsequently it has extended along the valley to Barkam, but with limited contact with the populations in Heishui and Lixian which belong to the nominate subspecies due to the altitudinal barrier (
Fig. 5
).
